I’ve often been asked the question, “how do you feel about faux plants?”. The answer is simple, not everyone has the light or the care level to have living plants in their space. So I’d rather you bring in a faux plant than force a living plant into a space where it will suffer and eventually die.  Faux plants can elevate spots in your home where you never thought you’d be able to have greenery before. With all of the faux plants in the Hilton Carter for Target collection, my goal was to make them look as real as possible so that they could really bring that lush, calm feeling. Here are a few tips on where and how to style them! 🌿🙏🏾💚

node.text: Over the holidays I partnered with @stgermaindrinks to develop some WILD ideas for entertaining during holiday season. To pull off these themed moments, I teamed up with the talented @sashabikoff and @madamebleu_stgermain. Inspired by the interactive nature of the Parisian salons in the 1920s, we chose three art movements from that time (Art Deco, Cubism and Surrealism) to take our holiday gatherings to the next level. Here are the highlights from the Surrealist nightcap moment and how it all came together! If you missed the Art Deco or Cubism moments, you can find them here in my IGTV. Enjoy! #StGermainPartner #SalonStGermain

node.text: I love each one of my books equally but I always get the question, “what’s the difference between the three of them?”. Well the answer is this, my first book WILD AT HOME tells my journey in greenery, basic plant care tips, plant styling tips, a small breakdown on how to propagate, 3 DIY projects and care tips on 10 highlighted plants. So maybe this one is for the plant newbie or someone that really wants to understanding styling. With WILD INTERIORS, it’s focus is on following others in the plant loving community, and hearing their journey in greenery. It features 12 amazing homes from around the world and you get to hear the stories of how these individual found themselves living with plants, what their routine is and how plants have transformed their lives. I then breakdown each room in the home and discuss how to style plants in each room and the best plants for those areas of the home. I then give you my top 10 inspiring green filled spaces and my top 10 “IT” plants and how to care for them. So maybe this one is for those looking to get inspiration for how to style their own plants at home, but also how to create a more wild interior. In my latest book, WILD CREATIONS, this time I decided to dig a lot deeper in plant care in a section I called “Plant Rants”. Here is where I speak on the importance of care, knowing everything from how to understand light, how to understand the importance of soil, how to properly water, pot and repot and at the end of the day, see plants as living things, NOT props. As I had in my previous two, I give you my 10 favorite plants of the moment and go deeper on how to care for them. Because I got 100 more pages than I did for WILD AT HOME, I also included 13 DIY projects, from how to build a plant chandelier, create a wall mounted plant, build a terrarium and many others. So maybe this one is for the more advanced plant parent or the doer out there that wants to create plant projects at home. Like I said, I love them equally, but through each one you can sense my ideas and journey changing and unfurling as well. For those of you that have one , two or all three of these books, thank you so much! 🙏🏾💚🌿

node.text: 6 years ago today I convinced my next door neighbor to go on a date with me. We didn’t have much in common. I was a filmmaker and she was a dentist. What would we talk about? We had zero friends in common. Who would bridge the gap? We didn’t listen to the same music. She was more Robyn while I was more 21 Savage. What would we dance to? All of these uncertainties created an immense amount of excitement. As we sat there during that dinner jumping from topic to topic, it was her laughter and ability to be her true self out the gate that sold me. It felt like a mutual, “take all of me or take nothing” sort of attitude was in the air that night. As I walked her to her front door, kissed her good night and then walked 20 feet to the next door that was mine, I thought, “I’m in a whole lot of trouble now.” But honestly she was. I tricked her into marrying me and then followed that up with helping me make a little version of her. 👼🏽😉 While we might not have matched up well on paper, in reality, our connection was magnetic. ❤️ #mylove

node.text: In 2014 I had the fortunate opportunity to vacation in Costa Rica with friends. While sitting alone on the beach one magic hour, a young dude rolled up on this bike with a young lady riding on the back. He proceeded to park it on this rock, hopped off, took her hand and walked into the water. I’m not going to lie, it was romantic af! I thought to myself, “shit, I wanna ride my boo on the back of a bike and jump in the ocean with her!” 😤 But then I thought, “first thing I need to do is learn how to ride a bike and second I need a boo that I love.” Long story short, found the boo…but I’m good on learning how to ride a bike. I’ll just carry her on my back. Anyways, here’s a #tbt for the romantics out there. Stay wild! 🖤 #love

node.text: When designing the remodel of our home, one of the goals was to make sure that from wherever you stood on the first floor, that you’d have the ability to look out of a window and see greenery. And not just from one position. From any spot, if you turned your head 180 degrees, you’d be able to see out of a minimum of 3 windows. The reason this was important is because our home is surrounded by many evergreen trees, so the windows allow for that blurring of indoor/outdoor. So in some cases, I’ve limited the amount of indoor plants in rooms so that the outdoor plants can make an impression. 🌿
